Gordon Ramsay is embroiled in a High Court row claiming he should not be held personally responsible for the £640,000-a-year rent of his London pub and restaurant.

The chef, who took on a 25-year-lease of the York and Albany in 2007, claims his signature as a personal guarantee for the pub's rent was forged using an automatic machine without his permission. 

Mr Ramsay acquired the property while his father-in-law, Christopher Hutcheson, was still at the helm of Gordon Ramsay Holdings before leaving in 2010 after he was accused  of plundering more than £1million from the company. 

