Following a lengthy legal dispute, he was reportedly given around £2million in a settlement and severed ties with the company.

Afterwards Mr Ramsay's lawyers discovered for the first time that the TV personality was personally guaranteeing the rent on the York and Albany in Regent's Park, the court heard today.

Mr Ramsay claims he never agreed to this and that his father-in-law used a Ghost Writer - a machine which reproduced Mr Ramsay's handwriting - to forge his signature.

Today he told of his 'shock and horror' that he believed his father-in-law had forged his signature, adding his 'deep and extensive trust in Hutcheson was entirely misplaced', and that he had defrauded him and the group 'hundreds of thousands of pounds'. 

The chef claims the machine had been acquired 'for purposes of merchandising only'. 

The owner of the pub, film director Gary Love, dismissed his allegations as 'absurd' and accused the chef of trying to wriggle out of his rental commitments. 

In 2007, Gordon Ramsay Holdings won a bidding war to secure a 25-year lease on the 160-year old building, while Mr Hutcheson was CEO of the company. 

